00:17:42,008 --> 00:17:44,533
What are you asking if they're married for?
They're with a fella.

230
00:17:44,610 --> 00:17:46,545
He's the lookout.

231
00:17:47,548 --> 00:17:49,813
Here's the Andrew Sisters,
ladies and gentlemen...

232
00:17:49,884 --> 00:17:53,513
Patty, Maxene and LaVerne.

233
00:17:53,588 --> 00:17:56,319
- Are you two girls married?
- I just asked that.

234
00:17:56,392 --> 00:17:59,487
Well, it got a laugh over there.
I figured it would get a laugh here.

235
00:18:13,045 --> 00:18:16,675
Ladies and gentlemen,
I want you to meet a singer-

236
00:18:16,750 --> 00:18:18,946
We've got a singer right now
named Hughie Hurd.

237
00:18:19,020 --> 00:18:21,853
<i>He's a great singer. I want you all</i>
<i>to, like, take care of him.</i>

238
00:18:21,922 --> 00:18:24,323
Give him a lot of applause, please,
because he's new in town.

239
00:19:04,641 --> 00:19:07,873
Man, he's putting them all to sleep.

240
00:19:13,151 --> 00:19:15,120
- Kill him, man. Get him off.
- What?

241
00:19:16,422 --> 00:19:19,290
What is this "bring the girls on"?
What kind of a place you running here?

242
00:19:22,796 --> 00:19:25,425
Bring the girls on.
Bring them on out.

243
00:19:25,500 --> 00:19:27,900
Call the girls, man.
Introduce the girls.

244
00:19:29,338 --> 00:19:32,102
- Good evening, ladies and gentlemen.
- Bring on the girls, will ya?

245
00:20:17,663 --> 00:20:21,828
Well, is everybody going
to sit around here all day?

246
00:20:23,703 --> 00:20:26,264
Dennis, stop that, will ya?
It makes me sick.

247
00:20:26,340 --> 00:20:30,141
- What's the matter with you, Tom? - I
got a hangover. That's what's the matter.

248
00:20:30,212 --> 00:20:32,476
That's what you get
for staying out all night.

249
00:20:32,548 --> 00:20:34,710
Who takes care of your sister
when you stay out all night?

250
00:20:34,784 --> 00:20:38,185
Man, I hire a babysitter. Don't I hire
a babysitter for you, sweetheart?

251
00:20:38,254 --> 00:20:40,883
David's writing a new novel
all about you, Ben.

252
00:20:40,958 --> 00:20:45,555
Better not be any of that
beat generation jazz like the last one.

253
00:20:46,565 --> 00:20:48,693
Stop it, Dennis. It makes me sick.

254
00:20:48,768 --> 00:20:51,669
Right in my coffee, Tom.

255
00:20:51,737 --> 00:20:53,501
Yeah, take some Dramamine.
It helps sometimes.

256
00:20:53,574 --> 00:20:57,534
- Dramamine? What's Dramamine?
- It's airsick medicine.

257
00:20:57,612 --> 00:21:00,274
I'm not airsick. I'm ground sick.

258
00:21:00,348 --> 00:21:02,977
But I'll take anything
if it'll help me with the way I feel.

259
00:21:03,052 --> 00:21:05,646
Dennis, will you do me a favor
and get me some of that stuff?

260
00:21:05,721 --> 00:21:08,384
- What is it? - Will you get me
some Dramamine, please?

261
00:21:08,458 --> 00:21:11,018
Do me a favor, huh?
Dennis, I appreciate that very much.

262
00:21:11,094 --> 00:21:13,723
Oh, Tom! Will you cut it out?
For crying out loud.

263
00:21:19,171 --> 00:21:21,106
You guys.

264
00:21:21,174 --> 00:21:25,235
You never break your pattern.
You'll never go anywhere with your lives.

265
00:21:25,312 --> 00:21:28,679
- Tom, take this. Drink up.
- How many do I take?

266
00:21:28,749 --> 00:21:30,684
Take just this one.

267
00:21:33,822 --> 00:21:36,690
<i>Why don't you do something,</i>
<i>learn something?</i>

268
00:21:36,759 --> 00:21:39,125
There are thousands of things to do
in New York City.

269
00:21:39,195 --> 00:21:43,428
- Like what?
<i>- Why don't you do something different?</i>

270
00:21:43,500 --> 00:21:45,435
<i>Do you want to meet new people?</i>

271
00:21:45,503 --> 00:21:47,562
You wanna come to a literary
party I'm having tonight?

272
00:21:47,639 --> 00:21:50,803
Don't invite them, David.
They won't even wear ties.

273
00:21:50,876 --> 00:21:53,710
- Lelia's coming.
- What the hell is a literary party?

274
00:21:53,780 --> 00:21:58,650
<i>Just where people interested in</i>
<i>books and other literary efforts...</i>

275
00:21:58,719 --> 00:22:00,653
get together and discuss things.

276
00:22:00,721 --> 00:22:02,849
Well, if they're coming,
I'm not going to be there...

277
00:22:02,924 --> 00:22:06,291
because they're gonna just act awful,
and I'll be so embarrassed.

278
00:22:06,361 --> 00:22:08,728
- Oh, it's all right.
<i>- Oh, a tie. You kidding?</i>

279
00:22:08,798 --> 00:22:11,062
<i>You can come just as you are.</i>
<i>Do you want to come?</i>

280
00:22:11,134 --> 00:22:14,263
- Yeah, I'll read a poem.
<i>- Don't get excited, honey.</i>

281
00:22:14,338 --> 00:22:17,740
Who wants to make
that fink party anyway?

282
00:22:17,809 --> 00:22:22,440
<i>All right, something else.</i>
<i>A concert or a museum?</i>

283
00:22:22,515 --> 00:22:26,612
A museum, I'm for it.
Ben, Tom?

284
00:22:26,687 --> 00:22:29,588
I don't think you've ever even been
in a museum, any of you.

285
00:22:29,656 --> 00:22:33,252
I? I've never been in a museum?

286
00:22:33,328 --> 00:22:36,924
<i>We've been in plenty of museums.</i>
<i>I bet you can't even spell it.</i>

287
00:22:36,999 --> 00:22:39,832
- Oh, will you stop teasing me?
- Here, Tom. Pick it up.

288
00:22:39,902 --> 00:22:42,167
Lelia has a very bright mind, Bennie.

289
00:22:42,238 --> 00:22:45,140
- She's developing very rapidly.
- Bull.

290
00:22:45,209 --> 00:22:49,373
I don't want to sit around here and
be insulted by these creeps. Let's go.

291
00:22:49,447 --> 00:22:52,281
Lelia, you should eat something
besides black coffee.

292
00:22:52,351 --> 00:22:56,948
David, please.
Don't start lecturing me now.

293
00:23:02,629 --> 00:23:05,064
Well?

294
00:23:05,133 --> 00:23:07,465
- Come on, David. Let's go.
- Never mind. We're going.

295
00:23:07,535 --> 00:23:10,733
What will it be, Dennis,
the Margarine or the Metropolitan?

296
00:23:10,806 --> 00:23:13,469
Let's go to the Metropolitan.
They got mummies there and everything.

297
00:23:13,543 --> 00:23:15,477
- What do you say?
- You guys kidding?

298
00:23:15,545 --> 00:23:18,674
- No, man. Let's cut.
<i>- Let's go.</i>

299
00:23:18,750 --> 00:23:21,344
- Let's go. Come on, Ben.
- Hey, Bennie.

300
00:23:21,419 --> 00:23:23,820
Come on, Ben. Let's go.

301
00:23:28,027 --> 00:23:30,359
Hey, Bennie, Dennis.

302
00:23:42,245 --> 00:23:44,736
I don't know what you wanted
to come here for, Dennis.

303
00:23:44,814 --> 00:23:48,012
This joint is nothing but a place
for a bunch of sexless women...

304
00:23:48,085 --> 00:23:50,019
who don't have
any love in their life.

305
00:23:50,087 --> 00:23:52,249
A lot of big deal professors.

306
00:23:52,323 --> 00:23:54,484
A lot of creeps trying to show
off how much they know.

307
00:23:54,559 --> 00:23:57,893
- You couldn't be wronger.
- I suppose professors don't come here?

308
00:23:57,963 --> 00:24:00,728
Well, I didn't say that.

309
00:24:00,801 --> 00:24:02,962
All right, Dennis. Look at that.

310
00:24:03,036 --> 00:24:05,528
I suppose you can tell me
what he's about, huh, genius?

311
00:24:05,606 --> 00:24:08,336
- He's a statue.
- I know he's a statue, Dennis.

312
00:24:08,409 --> 00:24:10,708
What kind of a statue?
I know he's a statue.

313
00:24:10,779 --> 00:24:14,045
- Well, Tom, I don't know everything.
- You know something, Dennis?

314
00:24:14,117 --> 00:24:16,608
- You don't know nothing.
- Oh, yeah? What do you know?

315
00:24:16,686 --> 00:24:18,678
- A lot more than you do, pal.
- Yeah?

316
00:24:18,756 --> 00:24:20,724
What you come here for
if you know so much?

317
00:24:20,791 --> 00:24:23,454
You have no respect for art,
no respect at all.

318
00:24:24,930 --> 00:24:26,864
You listen to me, Dennis.

319
00:24:26,932 --> 00:24:30,926
You're nothing but an ignorant slob,
Dennis, a little ignorant slob.

320
00:24:31,003 --> 00:24:33,029
<i>- I went to college, Dennis.</i>
<i>- You?</i>

321
00:24:33,106 --> 00:24:35,904
<i>All I ever got out of it</i>
<i>was dissipation...</i>

322
00:24:35,976 --> 00:24:39,003
<i>and a lot of early bells</i>
<i>disturbing my sleep.</i>

323
00:24:39,080 --> 00:24:41,014
<i>A lot of supercilious professors...</i>

324
00:24:41,082 --> 00:24:44,211
slob professors shooting off
their mouth about something...

325
00:24:44,286 --> 00:24:47,984
trying to teach me something they'd
already failed at in life themselves.

326
00:24:48,058 --> 00:24:50,549
So don't tell me
I don't appreciate anything.

327
00:25:05,245 --> 00:25:07,476
Tom, do you know what
I'm going to do with that?

328
00:25:07,548 --> 00:25:10,143
I'm gonna put it on a Christmas card.
Just a mask on a card.

329
00:25:10,218 --> 00:25:13,119
- Won't that be wild?
- Don't send one to me, pal.

330
00:25:13,188 --> 00:25:15,851
Look, Tom, will you cool it?
You know what you're talking about?

331
00:25:15,925 --> 00:25:18,052
I suppose you really understand
that thing, huh, Bennie?

332
00:25:18,127 --> 00:25:22,895
- It's not a question of understanding it.
If you feel it, you feel it, stupid.
- That's what I been trying to tell you.

333
00:25:22,966 --> 00:25:25,561
- Aw, shut up, Dennis.
- Aw, shut up, yourself.

334
00:25:25,637 --> 00:25:28,470
- Say you're sorry.
- All right, I'm sorry. Okay, I'm sorry.

335
00:25:28,540 --> 00:25:30,475
Hey, look at that one, now.
Look at that one, man.

336
00:25:30,543 --> 00:25:32,477
- You're really sorry?
- Yeah, I'm really sorry.

337
00:25:32,545 --> 00:25:34,878
- Okay. I apologize.
- Take it easy, guys, will you?

338
00:25:34,948 --> 00:25:36,882
Hey, look at this.
Now, look.

339
00:25:38,051 --> 00:25:40,384
<i>Now, look at this cat.</i>

340
00:25:40,454 --> 00:25:42,923
He really had a sense of humor
when he made this.

341
00:25:42,991 --> 00:25:45,050
That isn't supposed
to be humorous, Tom.

342
00:25:45,127 --> 00:25:48,359
What are we supposed to do,
get serious with a can like that?

343
00:25:48,431 --> 00:25:52,197
- I'm telling you right now, Tom.
- Don't get excited, Dennis.

344
00:25:52,269 --> 00:25:54,328
I'm not going to hurt it.
It's made of iron.

345
00:25:54,405 --> 00:25:56,339
A chick like that may destroy me.

346
00:25:56,407 --> 00:25:58,706
What's the matter with Tom?
Is he crazy or something?

347
00:25:58,777 --> 00:26:01,941
- No, Dennis.
- Someday you may marry
a girl that looks like that.

348
00:26:02,014 --> 00:26:05,780
- Oh, God forbid.
- It's not funny, Dennis.
- It's not funny.

349
00:26:09,489 --> 00:26:12,391
This joint gives me the creeps, Bennie.
Let's go, come on.

350
00:26:12,460 --> 00:26:15,361
- Where are you going?
- Let's get out of here.

351
00:26:15,430 --> 00:26:17,422
Okay.

352
00:26:25,376 --> 00:26:28,174
Lelia.

353
00:26:28,245 --> 00:26:30,544
I'm not trying
to hurt your feelings.

354
00:26:30,616 --> 00:26:34,074
But if you're going to write a story,
you have to do it professionally.

355
00:26:34,152 --> 00:26:36,644
David, I don't want to be a writer.

356
00:26:36,723 --> 00:26:39,716
I didn't want to do this.
You convinced me to do it.

357
00:26:39,793 --> 00:26:42,921
And now all you can do is criticize.

358
00:26:42,997 --> 00:26:45,990
I just want you to be honest.

359
00:26:46,067 --> 00:26:51,438
Look, your story has some pretty good
things. But it's very hard to be honest.

360
00:26:51,507 --> 00:26:53,169
I don't understand your viewpoint.

361
00:26:53,243 --> 00:26:57,270
Jean-Paul Sartre has absolutely nothing
to do with existential psychoanalysis.

362
00:26:57,347 --> 00:26:59,077
- Would you like a cigarette?
- No, thank you.

363
00:26:59,150 --> 00:27:01,414
Well, it's all a bit vague.
Don't you think so, Joan?

364
00:27:01,486 --> 00:27:03,614
I do not. The trouble with you is...

365
00:27:03,689 --> 00:27:06,817
you suffer from self-induced hysteria
at the word existentialism.

366
00:27:06,892 --> 00:27:08,884
- Are you aware of that?
- Can I fix you a drink?

367
00:27:08,962 --> 00:27:10,896
- No, thank you.
<i>- I assure you, I don't.</i>

368
00:27:10,964 --> 00:27:13,798
<i>I know the article to which you refer.</i>
<i>I've read it three times.</i>

369
00:27:13,868 --> 00:27:16,531
<i>I couldn't even find</i>
<i>the basic precepts.</i>

370
00:27:16,605 --> 00:27:19,574
- Which article was that?
<i>- If you can explain it, I'd be delighted.</i>

371
00:27:19,641 --> 00:27:22,873
Well, it's perfectly obvious.
Man, in contrast to other animals...

372
00:27:22,945 --> 00:27:24,879
is conscious of his own existence.

373
00:27:24,947 --> 00:27:28,111
Therefore, conscious of
the possibility of non-existence.

374
00:27:28,185 --> 00:27:30,654
<i>Ergo,</i> he has anxiety, right?

375
00:27:30,722 --> 00:27:32,656
Right, absolutely.
I couldn't agree with you more.

376
00:27:32,724 --> 00:27:35,717
Well, it figures.

377
00:27:41,168 --> 00:27:43,534
Now this girl here...

378
00:27:43,603 --> 00:27:45,970
she has no control over herself.

379
00:27:46,974 --> 00:27:49,409
She's been deeply hurt.

380
00:27:49,478 --> 00:27:51,412
And yet she goes on
as if nothing happened...

381
00:27:51,480 --> 00:27:53,414
living her life the same as before.

382
00:27:53,482 --> 00:27:57,044
It just doesn't make any sense.
Life takes more than imagination.

383
00:27:57,120 --> 00:28:02,058
Well, the point is that
if you're yourself, you won't get hurt.

384
00:28:02,126 --> 00:28:07,030
- Are you a writer too?
- Oh, no. Do I look like a writer?

385
00:28:07,099 --> 00:28:10,069
Well, I can't tell anymore.

386
00:28:10,136 --> 00:28:14,164
- I'm a dancer really.
<i>- Oh, a dancer. Why, that's great.</i>

387
00:28:14,241 --> 00:28:17,369
- Are you a ballet dancer?
- Oh, no, exotic.

388
00:28:17,445 --> 00:28:22,213
- Exotic?
<i>- Oh, you don't know what that is, do you?</i>

389
00:28:22,284 --> 00:28:27,086
- Not exactly.
- It's, uh, sort of modern...

390
00:28:27,157 --> 00:28:29,091
only more exotic.

391
00:28:29,159 --> 00:28:31,093
That sounds terrific.

392
00:28:31,161 --> 00:28:33,824
Listen, would you mind if I came
to see you perform sometime?

393
00:28:33,898 --> 00:28:36,265
<i>Oh, no. The very next time,</i>
<i>I'll invite you.</i>

394
00:28:36,335 --> 00:28:38,269
Great. When will that be?

395
00:28:38,337 --> 00:28:40,737
Oh, I'm not dancing right now.

396
00:28:40,806 --> 00:28:43,469
Oh, no? Why not?

397
00:28:43,543 --> 00:28:46,104
I'm going to have a baby in March.

398
00:28:47,548 --> 00:28:49,482
You're -

399
00:28:49,550 --> 00:28:51,485
That's great.
You're going to have a baby.

400
00:28:51,553 --> 00:28:55,752
A baby. That sounds terrific.
Congratulations. That's great news.

401
00:28:55,825 --> 00:28:58,487
- We think so, don't we, honey?
<i>- Huh?</i>

402
00:28:58,561 --> 00:29:01,622
Yeah, well, that's swell.
Congratulations.

403
00:29:01,698 --> 00:29:04,361
<i>- Thank you.</i>
- Listen, if it's okay...

404
00:29:04,435 --> 00:29:07,632
I'll just excuse myself
and fix my drink a little bit.

405
00:29:21,522 --> 00:29:26,358
<i>You don't know what it is to be hurt.</i>
<i>You can't always see it coming.</i>

406
00:29:26,428 --> 00:29:29,990
Sometimes a person could ruin your life.

407
00:29:30,066 --> 00:29:33,901
And yet, all he'd be able
to honestly say is "I'm sorry."

408
00:29:33,971 --> 00:29:36,701
Hi, David.
Am I interrupting something?

409
00:29:36,774 --> 00:29:40,472
Tony. Lelia Carruthers, Tony Russell.

410
00:29:40,545 --> 00:29:42,138
- Hello.
- Hello.

411
00:29:42,215 --> 00:29:44,308
I was just trying
to convince Lelia that...

412
00:29:44,383 --> 00:29:47,046
writers today have got to be
realistic in their approach.

413
00:29:47,120 --> 00:29:50,317
What he's trying to say is,
he hates my writing.

414
00:29:50,390 --> 00:29:52,916
You be the judge, Tony.
You be the judge.

415
00:29:52,994 --> 00:29:55,258
On her first day in New York this year...

416
00:29:55,330 --> 00:29:57,993
Lelia's writing about
a walk down Fifth Avenue.

417
00:29:59,001 --> 00:30:03,496
<i>She sees a stranger standing in</i>
<i>the sunlight on a street corner...</i>

418
00:30:03,573 --> 00:30:06,475
<i>and she walks up and kisses him,</i>
<i>this perfect stranger.</i>

419
00:30:06,544 --> 00:30:09,206
<i>It's revolting on a Sunday afternoon.</i>

420
00:30:09,280 --> 00:30:13,377
It is not.
If I wanted to, I would.

421
00:30:23,397 --> 00:30:26,231
Was that so bold?

422
00:30:26,301 --> 00:30:28,896
I guess I have to
change sides, David.

423
00:30:28,971 --> 00:30:31,963
David, would you go and get me
some more champagne?

424
00:30:32,041 --> 00:30:34,533
It's even more revolting in real life.

425
00:30:36,413 --> 00:30:38,348
Some more champagne.

426
00:30:39,350 --> 00:30:41,545
I think you've had plenty.

427
00:30:47,427 --> 00:30:50,760
- What did you say your name was?
- Lelia.

428
00:30:51,898 --> 00:30:54,390
It's a lovely party, isn't it?

429
00:30:54,468 --> 00:30:57,063
Do you know you're staring at me?

430
00:30:58,073 --> 00:31:01,805
- I'm hypnotizing you.
- Thank you.

431
00:31:01,878 --> 00:31:03,903
Who do you belong to, Lelia?

432
00:31:05,048 --> 00:31:06,983
Why, I belong to me.

433
00:31:07,051 --> 00:31:09,315
What about David?

434
00:31:12,390 --> 00:31:16,327
- No more champagne, Lelia.
- David, I was just about to see Lelia home.

435
00:31:16,395 --> 00:31:18,829
What do you mean?
I'm taking Lelia home.

436
00:31:18,898 --> 00:31:22,096
Well, uh, you're both wrong...

437
00:31:22,169 --> 00:31:24,467
because neither one of you
are taking me home.

438
00:31:24,538 --> 00:31:27,474
I'm meeting Vickie and
she's spending the night at my house.

439
00:31:27,542 --> 00:31:32,173
Oh. I guess my hypnotic spell is
a little rusty. What about tomorrow?

440
00:31:32,247 --> 00:31:35,183
Tomorrow, Lelia and I
are going to the park.

441
00:31:35,251 --> 00:31:37,811
<i>- Oh, well, good, good. I'll come along.</i>
- No.

442
00:31:37,887 --> 00:31:41,153
- Oh.
- David, don't be so unfriendly.

443
00:31:56,010 --> 00:31:59,310
Don't be such an old man, David.

444
00:31:59,381 --> 00:32:01,315
- Hi, Moe.
- Moe-Moe.

445
00:32:01,383 --> 00:32:04,751
Hey, baby.
Give me one of those.

446
00:32:05,755 --> 00:32:07,690
- Hello, stranger. There's a stranger.
- Hi, Moe.

447
00:32:07,758 --> 00:32:09,692
- Hello, Moe.
